U-TURN:

the transit transformation denounced as a disaster

By Julia-Simone Rutgers

Winnipeg Transit was never particularly popular. Unsurprising — any transit system with a reputation for leaving riders stranded in the cold while passing buses flash ‘Not in Service’ signs is unlikely to have many fans. Or all too many riders, for that matter.

Polling in 2023 found about one in ten Winnipeggers use the bus for their daily commute and half don’t use transit at all.

Some kind of change was inevitable. City council approved a “transit master plan” in 2021, charting a long-term path to modernization that would make riding the bus more convenient, accessible and attractive.

To get there, the city would need "an entirely new transit network."



On June 29 — practically overnight — that all-new “Primary Transit Network” hit the road, logging the first kilometres toward the public transit promised land.

“We expect it will improve things city-wide when we launch. More residents than ever will have access to frequent service,” transit planner Kevin Sturgeon said in February 2024.

The overhaul is the largest in transit’s 140-year history. But it’s hit one tiny roadblock: riders — especially many transit regulars — seem to hate it.



Complaints mostly centre around the keystone of the new network: the city is prioritizing frequent “spine” routes that make fewer stops and follow straighter paths to make transit more efficient and reliable.

The old system’s 87 routes and 5,200-ish bus stops have been stripped down to 71 routes and about 3,800 stops.



A little over a month in, some riders do report more frequent, on-time service and others have been able to commute by bus for the first time.

But for many, the changes means longer walks, inconvenient service hours and more transfers to get where they’re going — especially in residential areas.

The city removed 1,700 bus stops in all (and added about 450 new ones), but did not report exactly where they disappeared from.

The maps in this story uses data from the General Transit Feed Specification and the 2021 Census to take a closer look at the transit overhaul — and who it impacts most.

Where did the stops disappear from?

City-wide, Winnipeg has lost a little more than 2.5 bus stops per square kilometre.

The biggest losses were felt downtown and North End wards like Fort Rouge, Mynarski and Point Douglas seeing above-average losses.

Waverly West and Transcona (both of which saw population booms in recent years) have lost the fewest stops.

Who needs transit the most?

According to the 2021 Census, the downtown Daniel McIntyre neighbourhood hosts the highest share of low-income residents, followed by Fort Rouge, Mynarski and Point Douglas — and Waverly West.

These neighbourhoods also share top ranks when it comes to the proportion of residents taking the bus as part of their regular commute.

Many of these neighbourhoods fall along major roads and, therefore, more regular transit routes.

With those factors stacked together, the dark-green patches show areas where transit might already be a necessity.

In particular: the downtown core, the North End and communities surrounding Manitoba's largest university.

Here we find the discrepancies:

The downtown and north end wards with more transit users and more residents below the poverty line have lost more stops, on average, than other parts of the city.
Mynarski and Fort Rouge lost about 6 - 7 stops per sq. km. respectively — more than twice the city-wide average.
Wards like Waverly West, Transcona and St. Norbert, lost less than one stop per sq. km.

So...why?

The city says it's aiming for something called "bus stop balancing", where stops are fewer and farther between along more frequent routes.

Before the Primary Transit Network, the city found fewer than 2 in 5 homes were within a short walk of a frequent bus route. By frequent, they mean a bus that reliably arrives every 15 minutes.
The city aims to have about 75% of households within walking distance of frequent transit by 2045.

The new network has vastly expanded rapid transit reach. The estimated population within a 15 minute walk of a frequent bus stop has increased by 70%, and core neighbourhoods are well covered.

But balance is the key word. And critics of the network have pointed out that these rapid routes neglect residential areas, which have seen service cuts in the meantime. What good is an on-time bus stop that's too far to walk to, or isn't going where you need to be?


There's one more factor the city is trying to balance: transit isn't cheap. The first stages — including upcoming upgrades to transit infrastructure — are projected to cost upwards of $500 million, cost shared between all three levels of government. And there are already kinks to work out: the GPS has been on the fritz, spoiling the first month of real-time data about the new network; there aren't enough of the long, bendy buses yet to service all those new rapid routes, so pass-ups (when the bus is too full to stop) haven't also dissappeared overnight.

Each of the 1,720 missing bus stops saves the city a little cash. Replacing just one would cost close to $22K every year, per city estimates. Bringing them all back and adding more buses to service them? That could run up a bill of almost $4 million annually.



The good news is: Winnipeg Transit is open to feedback. These changes are one step toward the ultimate Transit Master Plan, and rider feedback will help form the long term shape of the new system. The bad news? The first adjustments are likely a year away. In the meantime, transit users will need to navigate Winnipeg's notoriously unforgiving winter — and that will really put this transit transformation to the test.
